        %h2 The Rise of Computers
        %p
            We live in a world where technology is becoming more and more integrated into our daily lives. With the rapid pace of technological innovation, the latest gadgets are
            = succeed '.' do
                %a{:href => "http://www.forbes.com/sites/lewisgersh/2013/07/29/the-velocity-of-obsolescence/", :target => :blank} becoming obsolete at an even faster rate
            Users constantly feel the need to upgrade their computers, phones, and tablets to the fastest, thinnest, and trendiest pieces of technology. However, it’s easy to forget the compounding global impact of setting increasingly short shelf lives on our sophisticated technologies.
        %p
            While we are accustomed to the idea of an international forward supply chain, users often fail to consider what happens to their products after they dispose of them. A reverse supply chain is the reuse, recycling, and disposal of products and their materials. The scale of these international reverse supply chains is significant; for instance, the export of waste and scrap and used goods from the United States
            = succeed ',' do
                %a{:href => "https://www.dosomething.org/facts/11-facts-about-e-waste", :target => :blank} was valued at $15 billion in 2005
            which accounted for 1.5% of total exports.
        %img{:src => "http://apploidnews.com/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/9ad44b71e90446548e9e9eb083c84603.jpg"}
