        %h2 Pollution and Energy
        %p
            As old models of computers continue to pile up in landfills, energy use and pollution are at an all-time high.
            %a{:href => "https://www.dosomething.org/facts/11-facts-about-e-waste", :target => :blank} Production of the average computer
            requires 530 pounds of fossil fuels, 48 pounds of chemicals, and 1.5 tons of water, an amount that quickly multiplies with the number of technological consumers in the world and the rate with which they replace their hardware.
        %p
            The problem is exacerbated by the fact that production is the most energy-demanding stage of a computer’s life.
            %a{:href => "http://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/es035152j", :target => :blank} 81% of the energy
            a computer expends in its lifetime is used in production, spread from mining precious metals for circuit boards to assembling the final piece of technology. Therefore, producing a new computer for each user every few years is particularly taxing on the environment.
        %img{:src => "http://i.huffpost.com/gen/1621413/images/o-CHINA-POLLUTION-FACTORY-facebook.jpg"}
        %p.center Pollution in China

