        %h2 E-waste
        %p
            In the past decade, e-waste has been also increasing. In 2010, totaling up computers, phones, and other pieces of technology in the United States, there were over 73 million units recycled and 310 million units trashed. Only 19.6% of the total 3.3 tons of e-waste was recycled.
        %img{:src => "http://www.electronicstakeback.com/wp-content/uploads/recycling_2000to2011.jpg", :style => "margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 20px;"}
        %p
            E-waste is piling up in landfills in the United States and foreign countries. While precise estimates remain unclear,
            %a{:href => "http://www.ban.org/E-waste/technotrashfinalcomp.pdf", :target => :blank} approximately 60% of end-of-life computers
            go abroad and are recycled by an
            = succeed '.' do
                %a{:href => recycling_path} informal or "backyard" industry
            Exporting this e-waste to developing countries is causing great harm to our environment.
        %p
            Computers contain toxic materials like lead, mercury, and arsenic, which are contained safely within the computer during use but which can be released during the recycling process, making them potentially dangerous. These toxic materials can leach from landfills and recycling centers into the surrounding environment if not properly treated.
        %p
